WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:11.560
Let's talk about designing a socially-critical data science course.

00:00:11.560 --> 00:00:15.360
I have for you a play in three acts.

00:00:15.360 --> 00:00:18.799
Act 1, teaching about wealth inequality.

00:00:18.799 --> 00:00:22.799
Act 2, data analysis for social action.

00:00:22.799 --> 00:00:29.080
And Act 3, specific resources to help you teach.

00:00:29.080 --> 00:00:32.720
Here's Act 1.

00:00:32.720 --> 00:00:36.880
Welcome to your first day of my class.

00:00:36.880 --> 00:00:44.840
The very first thing we do is that everyone gets one penny, an actual physical penny.

00:00:44.840 --> 00:00:51.160
The very next thing that we do is offer a prediction about the following.

00:00:51.160 --> 00:00:56.720
Everyone's going to do one trade with a classmate with your penny.

00:00:56.720 --> 00:00:57.840
How do you trade?

00:00:57.840 --> 00:00:59.799
You find another student.

00:00:59.799 --> 00:01:05.120
You bet against them on a random outcome event, like a coin flip or rock-paper-scissors.

00:01:05.120 --> 00:01:09.639
And the loser pays the winner one penny.

00:01:09.639 --> 00:01:13.160
Here's an abstract view of what my classroom would look like.

00:01:13.160 --> 00:01:16.839
Two students would find each other and pair up.

00:01:16.839 --> 00:01:18.800
There's one penny at stake.

00:01:18.800 --> 00:01:23.959
They're going to compete on a random outcome event and bet on the odds.

00:01:23.959 --> 00:01:28.480
And the loser is going to pay the winner one penny.

00:01:28.480 --> 00:01:38.440
So this happens across the classroom simultaneously with different students in different pairs.

00:01:38.440 --> 00:01:41.760
Before trading, we're all equal.

00:01:41.760 --> 00:01:47.559
If you were to look at a bar graph of everybody's wealth, it looks really uninteresting.

00:01:47.559 --> 00:01:49.779
Everybody's got one unit of money.

00:01:49.779 --> 00:01:51.199
It's a penny.

00:01:51.199 --> 00:02:00.360
And we've ordered these completely randomly, but each agent, as it were, has a bar.

00:02:00.360 --> 00:02:05.120
So the first question I ask before we even do the trade is, what's going to happen after

00:02:05.120 --> 00:02:08.119
everyone does one trade?

00:02:08.119 --> 00:02:10.399
I'd like you to imagine that.

00:02:10.399 --> 00:02:12.259
You each have a penny.

00:02:12.259 --> 00:02:14.759
You're going to match up with somebody else.

00:02:14.759 --> 00:02:15.759
You're going to bet on something.

00:02:15.759 --> 00:02:18.960
A coin flip is pretty handy because you both have pennies.

00:02:18.960 --> 00:02:26.199
And the loser is going to pay the winner one penny.

00:02:26.199 --> 00:02:34.139
So what happens after that happens is that half the people in the room go broke.

00:02:34.139 --> 00:02:41.000
And half the people in the room double their money instantly with one trade.

00:02:41.000 --> 00:02:45.240
Then you ask, what happens after lots of trades?

00:02:45.240 --> 00:02:53.679
That starts to look like this where you can see that a few people have most of the wealth.

00:02:53.679 --> 00:02:57.720
And there's even one person who's got five pennies, which means they quintupled their

00:02:57.720 --> 00:03:00.720
initial investment.

00:03:00.720 --> 00:03:06.479
But 71% of the people in this simulation are broke.

00:03:06.479 --> 00:03:11.479
Not poor, not impoverished, broke.

00:03:11.479 --> 00:03:15.000
Here's another case of us running it with slightly different rules and a greater money

00:03:15.000 --> 00:03:16.960
supply.

00:03:16.960 --> 00:03:17.960
I like this one a lot.

00:03:17.960 --> 00:03:19.440
It shows the same features.

00:03:19.440 --> 00:03:23.839
We have a few people with most of the wealth.

00:03:23.839 --> 00:03:30.119
But then you have people who go below the zero line with negative 20 wealth that they

00:03:30.119 --> 00:03:31.619
finished with.

00:03:31.619 --> 00:03:34.360
And you might be saying to yourself, is that an error in the graph?

00:03:34.360 --> 00:03:38.160
Or what happened?

00:03:38.160 --> 00:03:40.360
Loans happened.

00:03:40.360 --> 00:03:44.520
We allowed students to loan money at interest so they could loan four pennies with the expectation

00:03:44.520 --> 00:03:48.360
of getting five back, I think was the rule for that simulation.

00:03:48.360 --> 00:03:56.440
And the very first outcome was that the students constructed their own subprime loan crisis.

00:03:56.440 --> 00:03:57.539
Nobody was checking credit.

00:03:57.539 --> 00:04:02.199
So I watched one student hit the same person up for like five loans.

00:04:02.199 --> 00:04:08.119
And when she denied him a sixth loan, he walked across the classroom, found somebody else

00:04:08.119 --> 00:04:12.839
who didn't know him, and got more loans.

00:04:12.839 --> 00:04:17.799
The second outcome is that the students discovered the value of a distribution graph.

00:04:17.799 --> 00:04:21.040
So these bar graphs have the advantage of simplicity.

00:04:21.040 --> 00:04:26.079
But every time we run the simulation, we can't predict who's going to get most of the money.

00:04:26.079 --> 00:04:28.519
We just know that it's going to concentrate.

00:04:28.519 --> 00:04:32.799
And I do this on purpose because I want them to see that it's very difficult to predict

00:04:32.799 --> 00:04:35.799
the outcome of a bar graph.

00:04:35.799 --> 00:04:39.440
But if there's some underlying property that says, oh, most of the money is going to go

00:04:39.440 --> 00:04:44.279
to the few, that's the value of a distribution graph, that one distribution graph can represent

00:04:44.279 --> 00:04:47.040
so many different situations.

00:04:47.040 --> 00:04:52.359
So ultimately, we can't predict which agents will go broke, but we can predict that most

00:04:52.359 --> 00:04:53.760
will.

00:04:53.760 --> 00:05:02.040
Finally, I think it's important that a seemingly fair system can still produce unfair results.

00:05:02.040 --> 00:05:06.640
It seems fair because the coin toss is fair and everybody has an equal shot, but it's

00:05:06.640 --> 00:05:12.359
not fair because broke people routinely get denied the opportunity to trade again.

00:05:12.359 --> 00:05:16.040
If you had money, why would you trade with a broke person?

00:05:16.040 --> 00:05:21.760
You have a 50% chance of losing some money and a 50% chance of getting no money.

00:05:21.760 --> 00:05:23.440
That's it.

00:05:23.440 --> 00:05:30.279
So broke people stay broke, and they stay out of the simulation ultimately.

00:05:30.279 --> 00:05:35.279
Here's act two, data analysis for social action.

00:05:35.279 --> 00:05:40.399
So when I was teaching at Michigan State, a very local crisis was getting international

00:05:40.399 --> 00:05:45.359
attention, and it had to do with the poisoning of the water supply in Flint, Michigan.

00:05:45.359 --> 00:05:51.079
Flint's about an hour away from East Lansing, which is where I was teaching.

00:05:51.079 --> 00:05:56.920
The super short version is that to save money, the city of Flint decided to stop importing

00:05:56.920 --> 00:06:01.760
water from the Great Lakes and divert the Flint River instead, and the Flint River's

00:06:01.760 --> 00:06:07.359
toxic corrosiveness leached lead out of the pipes.

00:06:07.359 --> 00:06:12.480
This was happening while we were teaching the course, and a data set had just come out

00:06:12.480 --> 00:06:21.720
from folks at Virginia Tech who had sent at-home testing kits to 270 families in Flint to get

00:06:21.720 --> 00:06:24.239
readings on their water levels.

00:06:24.239 --> 00:06:28.359
And we had students analyze this and write about it.

00:06:28.359 --> 00:06:32.799
Here's one example of a student analysis where what they've done is try to compute the number

00:06:32.799 --> 00:06:37.040
of samples that exceed the EPA's action limit.

00:06:37.040 --> 00:06:42.000
So the EPA says if more than 10% of your samples are above this threshold, which happens to

00:06:42.000 --> 00:06:48.160
be .015 milligrams per liter, I think, you've got a problem.

00:06:48.160 --> 00:06:52.559
And a student wrote some code to count up how many of the raw samples there are that

00:06:52.559 --> 00:06:57.359
exceed that amount, as well as the percentage that exceed that amount.

00:06:57.359 --> 00:07:01.880
The other thing I want to point out to you is it's difficult to see, perhaps, but that

00:07:01.880 --> 00:07:04.959
distribution has a real long tail.

00:07:04.959 --> 00:07:13.920
And there are some folks out there at .2 or, yeah, sorry, .12, .14, six, eight times the

00:07:13.920 --> 00:07:17.200
legal limit for lead.

00:07:17.200 --> 00:07:19.399
That's a huge problem.

00:07:19.399 --> 00:07:25.160
So we had our students write to the governor of Michigan with their analysis results.

00:07:25.160 --> 00:07:26.600
And here's an example student one.

00:07:26.600 --> 00:07:28.600
I constructed a histogram.

00:07:28.600 --> 00:07:33.559
I also wrote a simple program to compute the number of samples and the percentage above

00:07:33.559 --> 00:07:34.559
the limit.

00:07:34.559 --> 00:07:40.760
Forty-five samples exceeded the EPA limit, making this 16.6% of the samples above the

00:07:40.760 --> 00:07:42.519
action limit.

00:07:42.519 --> 00:07:48.600
This indicates the seriousness of this problem and exactly why we need to urgently take action

00:07:48.600 --> 00:07:53.440
to help Flint.

00:07:53.440 --> 00:07:56.839
Act three, resources to help you teach.

00:07:56.839 --> 00:08:00.380
You might be asking, what can I do?

00:08:00.380 --> 00:08:03.720
So I have three pieces of advice that I'm going to go into detail on.

00:08:03.720 --> 00:08:11.760
The first is try to choose data and activities that question systems of power.

00:08:11.760 --> 00:08:20.079
The second is do what you can to make bias issues in your data known and check for them.

00:08:20.079 --> 00:08:25.079
And the third, which I think is arguably the most important, is to adopt a critical framework

00:08:25.079 --> 00:08:30.880
to analyze and expose oppression.

00:08:30.880 --> 00:08:35.039
So first up, you should use the opportunity of being able to choose data sets for your

00:08:35.039 --> 00:08:41.559
class to analyze to ask what issues demand our attention socially.

00:08:42.359 --> 00:08:45.559
Now, I don't want to stand here and say that every activity that you do must always be

00:08:45.559 --> 00:08:48.080
focused on improving the social good.

00:08:48.080 --> 00:08:52.960
But I think even if you started with one activity, you'd find it has a ripple impact, and it

00:08:52.960 --> 00:08:56.960
gets you thinking about more data that can do this, and it gets your students thinking

00:08:56.960 --> 00:09:01.840
about more ways they can try and help society through the newfound powers they're learning

00:09:01.840 --> 00:09:04.520
in your courses.

00:09:04.520 --> 00:09:08.919
Second, you can check data for biases.

00:09:08.919 --> 00:09:13.159
You can ask who is being disadvantaged in this data.

00:09:13.159 --> 00:09:20.159
And so a tool for that is IBM's AI360.

00:09:20.159 --> 00:09:23.760
I've got the link down there, but also I'll have a QR code you can scan, which has all

00:09:23.760 --> 00:09:28.159
the links that are related to this presentation, so don't panic.

00:09:28.159 --> 00:09:33.559
The AI360 has some demo data that you can take a look at, and this is an example of

00:09:33.559 --> 00:09:35.460
what it can produce for you.

00:09:35.460 --> 00:09:40.380
This data was analyzed and has a privileged group, which happen to be females, and an

00:09:40.380 --> 00:09:45.260
unprivileged group, which happen to be males, because we have representational issues of

00:09:45.260 --> 00:09:47.260
unequal weighting.

00:09:47.260 --> 00:09:51.900
So the tool goes on to determine things like what would the statistical parity difference

00:09:51.900 --> 00:09:57.859
be, what's the equal opportunity difference, what's the average odds difference.

00:09:57.859 --> 00:10:06.020
And then it goes so far as to offer strategies for addressing that bias.

00:10:06.020 --> 00:10:09.700
These are two of the automated strategies that it proposes, reweighting and optimized

00:10:09.700 --> 00:10:10.700
preprocessing.

00:10:10.700 --> 00:10:15.840
I think a third is adversarial learning, but I don't know that much about adversarial learning,

00:10:15.840 --> 00:10:17.940
so don't quote me on that.

00:10:17.940 --> 00:10:23.419
But the idea is that the tool lets you see where your data might be leading you to conclusions

00:10:23.419 --> 00:10:31.200
that are steered by biases that, in most cases, we want to correct for, and it offers

00:10:31.200 --> 00:10:36.979
automated solutions for doing so.

00:10:36.979 --> 00:10:40.820
My third point is about adopting a critical framework.

00:10:40.820 --> 00:10:48.099
I think it's so important to recognize that data analyses are not value neutral.

00:10:48.099 --> 00:10:52.940
So this is a book called Data Feminism that came out in 2020 from MIT Press.

00:10:52.940 --> 00:10:57.340
You can read the entire thing for free at their website, which, again, will be in my

00:10:57.340 --> 00:11:00.859
list of links in my QR code thing.

00:11:00.859 --> 00:11:03.820
Here's a quote from a description of the book.

00:11:03.820 --> 00:11:10.119
Illustrating data feminism in action, D'Ignazio and Klein show how challenges to the male-female

00:11:10.119 --> 00:11:17.020
binary can help challenge other hierarchical and empirically wrong classification systems.

00:11:17.020 --> 00:11:21.979
It's a little jargony, so let's do this.

00:11:22.020 --> 00:11:28.140
Raise your hand if you've either seen or yourself done gender as a dichotomous variable, zero

00:11:28.140 --> 00:11:32.059
or one.

00:11:32.059 --> 00:11:37.739
So what happens when your gender is not captured by zero or one, or male or female?

00:11:37.739 --> 00:11:45.179
Well, you could add another option, like non-gender conforming, but what happens if your gender

00:11:45.179 --> 00:11:48.659
is just non-binary or your gender is gender fluid?

00:11:48.659 --> 00:11:50.940
You could add options until the cows come home.

00:11:50.940 --> 00:11:57.900
Basically what's being revealed to you is an oppressive system that is forcing people

00:11:57.900 --> 00:12:03.200
into categories that they don't necessarily identify with, or is forcing them to exclude

00:12:03.200 --> 00:12:07.700
themselves from the data analysis entirely just by not answering the question.

00:12:07.700 --> 00:12:12.500
And D'Ignazio and Klein are trying to point out it's stuff like that that we might not

00:12:12.500 --> 00:12:17.239
even be consciously aware of if we're not thinking for it that can have huge impacts

00:12:17.239 --> 00:12:23.099
on the people we're asking questions of.

00:12:23.099 --> 00:12:26.599
My final example comes from mapping Detroit.

00:12:26.599 --> 00:12:29.239
I call this redlining in action.

00:12:29.239 --> 00:12:34.719
This was a map that was produced in 1929 by an all-white, all-male chamber of commerce

00:12:34.719 --> 00:12:39.239
and a majority white male federal home loan board.

00:12:39.239 --> 00:12:44.679
The purpose of the map was to figure out neighborhoods where it was risky to offer people loans and

00:12:44.679 --> 00:12:48.919
neighborhoods where it was safe to offer people loans.

00:12:48.919 --> 00:12:56.599
The effect of the map is that an already racially segregated demographic is now disproportionately

00:12:56.599 --> 00:13:07.960
affected by people's decisions not to lend to, for example, black people because those

00:13:07.960 --> 00:13:10.880
were deemed neighborhoods where it was risky to lend.

00:13:10.880 --> 00:13:16.679
So can you imagine if your credit worthiness depended not on yourself but on who's next

00:13:16.679 --> 00:13:18.679
to you?

00:13:18.679 --> 00:13:21.799
Imagine how that crushes social mobility.

00:13:21.799 --> 00:13:26.799
Imagine how that reifies social order.

00:13:26.799 --> 00:13:31.799
D'Ignazio and Klein say early 20th century redlining maps had an aura very similar to

00:13:31.799 --> 00:13:34.520
the big data approaches of today.

00:13:34.520 --> 00:13:39.520
These high-tech scalable solutions were deployed across the nation, and there were one method

00:13:39.520 --> 00:13:46.280
among many that worked to ensure that wealth remained attached to the racial category of

00:13:46.280 --> 00:13:53.919
whiteness, that wealth remained attached to the racial category of whiteness.

00:13:53.919 --> 00:13:58.159
I think it's worth asking, if that's what data science was doing then, what's it doing

00:13:58.159 --> 00:13:59.159
now?

00:13:59.159 --> 00:14:00.159
Thanks, folks.

00:14:00.799 --> 00:14:01.799
Thanks, folks.

00:14:01.799 --> 00:14:01.799


